<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Suaeda moquinii </i>is a woody subshrub with linear, fleshy leaves that are yellowish green to red. Plants are short-lived, and they senesce in large groups. The small seeds establish easily following rain, and even-age stands appear to develop after periods of favorable moisture conditions. Observations in the Mojave Desert suggest that <i>S. moquinii </i>tolerates less flooding than does <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis </i>(Young and Young 1986). <i>Suaeda nigra </i>is the current accepted taxon name for <i>Suaeda moquinii </i>(UCB 2008).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Isocoma acradenia </i> is a woody subshrub with erect or ascending stems which are a shiny yellowish white, aging to a yellow-gray. It has oval-shaped gray-green glandular leaves sometimes with stumpy teeth along the edges. Leaves are often in axillary fascicles and age to pale gray or tan. The inflorescences are made of clusters of four or five flower heads with whitish-indurate phyllaries with apical resin pockets bearing many golden yellow disc flowers. The fruits are small achenes with yellowish pappus. There are three varieties of this species found in southwestern U.S. and northwest Mexico.<br/>
<br/>
The alliance is restricted primarily to alkaline substrates in desert or semi-desert habitats. Stands are floristically and structurally simple; however, plant cover may vary substantially (2% to > 80%). We know little about disturbance effects, though <i>S. moquinii </i>appears opportunistic in occupying roadsides and other recently disturbed areas.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been updated to include associations dominated or codominated by <i>Isocoma acradenia</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
