    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ag, Ai-k). Stands occur from Carrizo Plain around Soda Lake (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011) and the southern end of Temblor Range to the Kettleman Hills and north to the Livermore Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands are widespread in alkali areas. Stands in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park occupy playa borders and adjacent lower bajadas, as well as alkaline terraces above washes (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b); they are mixed with stands of the <i>Atriplex canescens</i> and <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, At-z). Stands occur in the San Joaquin Valley in a fine scale matrix with those of <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> and <i>Sporobolus airoides</i> alliances, depending on the depth of the water table.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Stands are widespread throughout the section. They usually occupy low-lying alkaline playas and basins (Bradley 1970, Thomas et al. 2004, CDFW 2013). An exception is the eastern shore of Owens Dry Lake, where stands ascend onto lower bajadas of the Inyo Mountains and mix with stands of the <i>Atriplex confertifolia</i> and <i>Atriplex hymenelytra</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-i). Stands occur near Fish Slough (Odion et al. 1992a, CDW 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc). Stands occur in the Surprise Valley bordering the Alkali Lakes with stands of <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> alliance. Stands also occur at Honey Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands occur around playas throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc). Stands occur within alkaline basins and on sandy substrates in the Saline Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bk). Stands in the San Jacinto Wildlife Area occupy alkali flats and scalds on clay soils along with CNPS list 1B plant <i>Atriplex coronata</i> var. <i>notatior</i> (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance primarily occurs on alkaline substrates or alkali sinks; areas with alkali soils have historically and are currently being converted for agriculture and urban development. Loss of habitat in the San Joaquin Valley has been intense due to conversion of crops, grazing, and water diversion. Stands of this vegetation type can also be heavily impacted by non-native plant species, especially non-native annual grasses.

Alkaline soils are “reclaimed” for agriculture by treating soils with amendments such as gypsum that leach the salts from the soil through irrigation (Barbour et al. 2016). This practice alters the soil chemistry in such a way that restoration becomes impractical (Jones & Stokes 2006). Much of the remaining alkaline habitats in California are located on state and federal lands.

These plant communities may be particularly vulnerable to wildfire as well, especially where the proliferation of non-native annual grasses have increased fire intensity (BLM 2008).

Alkali sink communities such as this alliance provide habitat to many species that are being impacted by loss of habitat such as the Tipton kangaroo rat, an endangered species endemic to the San Joaquin Valley (Cypher et al. 2016). </div>
</div>

    

    

